1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,357
[INTRO]

2
00:00:00,657 --> 00:00:02,442
The internet is a paradox.

3
00:00:02,742 --> 00:00:04,528
Always connected, yet deeply lonely.

4
00:00:04,828 --> 00:00:06,614
You find a killer video.

5
00:00:06,914 --> 00:00:09,414
The first instinct is to share it.

6
00:00:09,714 --> 00:00:12,571
But sharing a link is a dead end.

7
00:00:12,871 --> 00:00:15,728
You want to watch *at the same time*.

8
00:00:16,028 --> 00:00:17,457
Rtwatch is the answer.

9
00:00:17,757 --> 00:00:18,828
Built on WebRTC.

10
00:00:19,128 --> 00:00:20,914
Peer-to-peer viewing that actually works.

11
00:00:21,214 --> 00:00:21,571
[HOOK]

12
00:00:21,871 --> 00:00:24,371
I am extremely picky about my tools.

13
00:00:24,671 --> 00:00:28,600
If an app asks for my email, I close the tab.

14
00:00:28,899 --> 00:00:32,114
If it wants a login, I block the site.

15
00:00:32,414 --> 00:00:34,557
Rtwatch passes the vibe check instantly.

16
00:00:34,857 --> 00:00:36,285
No signup. No tracking.

17
00:00:36,585 --> 00:00:38,728
Just a link and a promise.

18
00:00:39,028 --> 00:00:45,457
The promise is simple: You and your friend see the exact same frame at the exact same time.

19
00:00:45,757 --> 00:00:47,899
It delivers on that promise flawlessly.

20
00:00:48,199 --> 00:00:48,557
[BODY]

21
00:00:48,857 --> 00:00:50,285
The secret is WebRTC.

22
00:00:50,585 --> 00:00:52,014
Real-time communication between browsers.

23
00:00:52,314 --> 00:00:54,814
It cuts out the corporate middleman completely.

24
00:00:55,114 --> 00:00:59,399
When you press pause, a signal goes *directly* to your friend's browser.

25
00:00:59,699 --> 00:01:03,628
No server handshake. No database write. No polling every three seconds.

26
00:01:03,928 --> 00:01:05,357
Just pure, low-latency action.

27
00:01:05,657 --> 00:01:07,799
It makes the experience feel intimate.

28
00:01:08,099 --> 00:01:12,028
Like you are passing the remote control on a real couch.

29
00:01:12,328 --> 00:01:14,828
This is how technology should feel. Immediate.

30
00:01:15,128 --> 00:01:15,485
[EXAMPLE]

31
00:01:15,785 --> 00:01:16,857
Paint this picture.

32
00:01:17,157 --> 00:01:17,871
Friday night.

33
00:01:18,171 --> 00:01:21,028
Your buddy is in Berlin. You're in Austin.

34
00:01:21,328 --> 00:01:26,328
You want to watch a terrible 90s action movie on a random streaming site.

35
00:01:26,628 --> 00:01:28,057
You pull up Rtwatch.

36
00:01:28,357 --> 00:01:31,214
You drop the direct link to the video.

37
00:01:31,514 --> 00:01:32,585
That is it.

38
00:01:32,885 --> 00:01:34,671
The interface is brutally simple.

39
00:01:34,971 --> 00:01:37,828
You send the generated link to your friend.

40
00:01:38,128 --> 00:01:39,199
They open it.

41
00:01:39,499 --> 00:01:40,571
Boom. Synced perfectly.

42
00:01:40,871 --> 00:01:44,799
No "Can you hear me?" No "Is it playing for you?"

43
00:01:45,099 --> 00:01:47,242
Just shared cultural chaos in real-time.

44
00:01:47,542 --> 00:01:47,899
[BODY2]

45
00:01:48,199 --> 00:01:50,342
Why doesn't every app do this?

46
00:01:50,642 --> 00:01:54,214
Because big platforms don't want you to have direct connections.

47
00:01:54,514 --> 00:01:57,014
They want you in their walled garden.

48
00:01:57,314 --> 00:01:59,457
They want to serve you ads.

49
00:01:59,757 --> 00:02:02,614
They want to data mine your chat history.

50
00:02:02,914 --> 00:02:06,485
Rtwatch is a political statement disguised as a simple utility.

51
00:02:06,785 --> 00:02:09,999
It says the internet belongs to the users again.

52
00:02:10,299 --> 00:02:13,514
It prioritizes human connection over the corporate bottom line.

53
00:02:13,814 --> 00:02:17,028
That radical subtraction is exactly why I love it.

54
00:02:17,328 --> 00:02:17,685
[BODY3]

55
00:02:17,985 --> 00:02:19,414
For the developers watching.

56
00:02:19,714 --> 00:02:21,142
Look at this project.

57
00:02:21,442 --> 00:02:23,585
It is a masterclass in restraint.

58
00:02:23,885 --> 00:02:25,314
Solve one problem perfectly.

59
00:02:25,614 --> 00:02:27,399
Respect the user's privacy obsessively.

60
00:02:27,699 --> 00:02:30,199
Use the right tool for the job.

61
00:02:30,499 --> 00:02:31,928
WebRTC is notoriously tricky.

62
00:02:32,228 --> 00:02:34,014
NAT traversal is a nightmare.

63
00:02:34,314 --> 00:02:37,528
Rtwatch handles the complexity so you don't have to

